Introduction to statsmodels

Published: Tue 26 April 2022
By PB

In Programming.

tags: python statsmodels

While not as commonly used as scikit-learn, statsmodels is a relatively new and very powerful statistical package for Python. For users of R, this package will feel very familiar as it can support formula and returns many of the values of R's base and stats libraries.

In this series, we'll focus on loading in some daily minimum temperature data from 1-1-1981 to 12-31-1990 and then fitting a Linear Regression (and when I write this, I mean a standard OLS regression) model to this data. We'll discuss:

  1. (very briefly) The patsy library; a very useful library when doing modeling that also mirrors some R functionality.
  2. We'll fit a simple linear regressor and show how this matches with sklearn but gives you more metrics
  3. We'll go through using radial basis functions to fit the data. If you've never seen basis functions before, you'll love them! They allow you to inject non-linearity into your OLS models and are very powerful (more on that later).

So to get started, let's load a few basic libraries and the data. NOTE: I'm writing this in a Docker container so the data load is a bit more complex than just loading the data locally.

# Let's split the data into training and test sets based on dates.  We'll keep 1990 as our test set.
train_df = temp_df.loc[temp_df['Date'] <= pd.to_datetime('1989-12-31')]
test_df = temp_df.loc[temp_df['Date'] >= pd.to_datetime('1990-01-01')]

Patsy¶

Now it's time to import patsy. The main functionality of patsy is to create matrices based on formulas. This mimics native behavior of R and can be very very helpful in Python, even when not planning on using statsmodels.

This includes more complicated formulas, e.g. y ~ x1 + time*(log(x2)-log(x3)). In addition to this, patsy can create dummy columns for categories AND handle redundancy so that columns don't become linearly dependent, and even factor-level interaction terms. This is all beyond the scope of this talk, but it's a wonderful library that I would highly recommend to anyone as part of their modeling pipeline.

In our case, we'll just use them in the future to make matrices to feed into our linear models:

In [6]:
# Import patsy to make our modeling work easier
from patsy import dmatrices

# Naming the formula for the linear regression; here we just think temperature depends on a trend term
# NOTE: The intercept term is implicit; if we wanted to change that, simply write:
#           "Temp ~ 0 + Time"
formula1 = "Temp ~ Time"
# Use Patsy to make the required matrices/arrays
y_train, X_train = dmatrices(formula1, data = train_df)
y_test, X_test = dmatrices(formula1, data = test_df)

To see what's actually happening under the hood, let's call the function one more time and just look at the output.

import statsmodels.api as sm

# Train the model using our training data
lin_mod1 = sm.OLS(y_train, X_train)
# Fitting the models
lm1_results = lin_mod1.fit()
# Check our stats!
print(lm1_results.params)

# Creating predictions for plotting/scoring purposes
y_pred_train_lm1 = lm1_results.predict(X_train)
y_pred_test_lm1 = lm1_results.predict(X_test)

[ 1.11764069e+01 -3.24615547e-05]

You can see that the general procedures are nearly identical! The only additional steps we perform are creating some predictions for plotting and performance analysis. We conclude by printing out the coefficients and as you can see, they two methods agree in the results. But consider how you assess the model in sklearn.

Normally we would run cross validation and pick some metrics to evaluate on. But really, all we can do is compare certain models to others (or baselines) and maybe assess some plots. This is far from the most scientific evaluation process. This is where statsmodels differentiates itself from sklearn. Instead of just putting out coefficients or scoring on some metrics, we now have a large number of statistical tests:

This provides a great amount of useful statistical information to the DS/ML practitioner. The downside is that there is a large amount of information and parsing it out can be difficult and require a more detailed background in statistics. I'll put a summary of the metrics below (with links) that you can follow later if you want.

Fields/Metrics you should always look at:¶

  1. Dep. Variable - Always good to make sure you are predicting what you think you are predicting.
  2. R-squared/Adj. R-Squared - This shows the proportion of variance in $\vec{y}$ that is explained by the independent variables $\mathbb{X}$ with 0 being the answer you would get if you predict the $\bar{y}$. It is bounded above by 1 (perfect explanation) and can go to $-\infty$ (terrible). See following Wikipedia link for more details about $R^{2}$ and $Adj. R^{2}$
  3. Prob (F-Statistic) - Most classical Linear Regression models will compute an ANOVA on the model to test the hypothesis that all coefficients are 0 (outside of the intercept). I'd highly recommend section 6.2 of Plane Answers to Complex Problems for a wonderful treatment of this.
  4. The t and P>|t| regression values - Since each of the coefficients follows a $t$-distribution under the model hypothesis, we can use these tests to see which coefficients appear to belong in the model. So knowing the t-values and associated probablities can be very helpful in determining feature selection. Sections 2.7 & 6.2 of Plane Answers to Complex Problems have great details on this.
  5. Prob(Omnibus) and Prob(JB) - These metrics relate to Omnibus and Jarque-Bera (JB) tests respectively. Both are tied to the notion of Skew and Kurtosis and relate to assessing the Gausian assumption of the model. The Omnibus metric is actually D'Agostino's K-squared-test and you can read the associated link as well as this link for more details on Jarque-Bera.

Additional Metrics¶

  1. AIC/BIC$^{\star}$ - These are two functions based on the log-likelihood of the model that penalize you for the number of paramters you have (BIC the most strongly). These only make sense when you are running multiple models though as a means for comparing performance. We usually do make multiple runs though, so just good to keep in the back of your mind. More details on AIC and BIC are available here.
  2. Durbin-Watson - The Durbin-Watson test checks the assumption of independent observations (rather than corrrelation). The reason this isn't a "Must See" is because you would have to manually find the critical values. An "okay" rule of thumb is that any values between 1.5 and 2.5 are okay.
  3. Cond. No. - This is matrix technique to see if there is any multi-collinearity in the data. This can be misleading though depending on the scale of the data. Section 15.1 of Plane Answers to Complex Problems defines this more clearly.
  4. Skew and Kurtosis - It's a good idea to look at these as well, as it may help you see a significant problem highlighed by Prob(Omnibus) and Prob(JB).

Normaly we plot the data quickly when possible to help gain intuition, but in this case I thought it would be good to see the statistics first before looking at the plot. I did this to show that the statistical outputs are helpful in assessing the fit. We note that the fit is poor ($R^{2}$ = 0, $P(F-Stat) = 0.66$, etc...). The "traditional" approach that is used to add some periodicity to the data is to add an indicator function for each month (and dropping the intercept term). Unfortunately the fits are far from realistic, appearing like some kind of periodic staircase. To improve this you could have indicator functions for weeks or even specific days, which will make the plots smoother, but at the cost of injecting a great deal of variance into the model, with each point having very few training points. Fortunately, we can do quite a bit more if we want, but it will involve some extra concepts AND shattering a major myth about Linear Regression.

Nearly every course on ML begins by covering traditional Linear Regression. Yet in nearly most cases (particularly in courses that do not emphasize Statistical ML), the technique is marginalized by instructors who say things like "We are looking at this to build intuition, but nobody really uses this any more because all it can do is make lines/hyperplanes", or words to that effect. At first glance, this reasoning may seem reasonable (it is called "Linear" Regression after all), but it turns out this is completely false!

More formally, a Linear Regression model assumes that (given a label, feature vector pair: $(y, \vec{\pmb{x}})$) that $$y = \vec{\pmb{\theta}}^{\top}\vec{\pmb{x}} + \epsilon,~~\mathbb{E}[\epsilon|\vec{\pmb{x}}] = \mathbb{E}[\epsilon] = 0.$$ Note that $\vec{\pmb{x}}$ does not have any non-unitary exponents and therefore the resulting dot product is a simple linear sum of vector elements: $$\vec{\pmb{\theta}}^{\top}\vec{\pmb{x}} = \sum_{i = 1}^{k}w_{i}\cdot x_{i}.$$ But consider a hypothetical example where $\vec{\pmb{x}} = [1~~x_{1}]^{\top}$ and $\vec{\pmb{\theta}} = [\theta_{0}~~\theta_{1}]^{\top}$. If we created a new variable, $x_{2} := x_{1}^{2}$ and defined $\vec{\pmb{x}'} := [1~~x_{1}~~x_{2}]^{\top}$ and $\vec{\pmb{\theta}'} := [\theta_{0}~~\theta_{1}~~\theta_{2}]^{\top}$, would it be valid to try and model $y = \vec{\pmb{\theta}'}^{\top}\vec{\pmb{x}'}$? Of course it would! From an equation point-of-view, there the two equations are identical in the abstract sense, even though one of the columns is a nonlinear function of another. If you are still unconvinced, try and estimate this in your own programming language of choice to confirm this if you want; the machinery has no idea that one column is a square of the other.

So why is it called "Linear" regression, when we clearly can have columns that are non-linear functions of other columns? This is because Linear Regression is not required to be linear in $\vec{\pmb{x}}$; instead it must be linear in $\vec{\pmb{\theta}}$! Put in other words, we can solve $$y = \vec{\pmb{\theta}}^{\top}\phi\left(\vec{\pmb{x}}\right) + \epsilon$$ where $$\phi:\mathbb{R}^{k}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}^{l}$$ where (typically in practice) $k < l$. To make this more concrete, we can have valid regression models when we use Basis Functions (the $\phi(\cdot)$ functions referenced earlier). Now in this case, I'm going to skip using a Fourier basis function which would likely be a great decision given this (clearly periodic) data, and instead utilize a Gaussian Radial Basis Function. To do this, we need to do a bit of grunt work first.

In [15]:
# Let's put some radial basis functions in for fun
# We'll make a new version of the training and test feature data
train_df1 = train_df.copy()
test_df1 = test_df.copy()

# We'll create a function to find an rbf. The function takes in some "centerpoint" known as `datestart`
# and then converts that centered point into the current year of the record in the data. It then finds
# the delta between the date in question and the current date of the record, accounts for deltas in years 
# and returns the function valuated at that point with our given `gamma` parameter
def rbf_date(df, datestart, gamma):
    date = pd.to_datetime(datestart)
    mo = date.month
    dy = date.day
    raw_delta = (df['Date'] - pd.Timestamp(year = df['Year'], month = mo, day = dy)).days
    delta = min(np.abs(raw_delta), np.abs(raw_delta + 365) , np.abs(raw_delta - 365))
    return np.exp(-gamma * (delta) **2)
In [16]:
# Let's make one basis function per month:
num_rbfs = 12

# We now want to make the actual centerpoints for the functions. This code will use list comprehension
# to make a spike centered on the 1st of every month of 2020.
# NOTE: you can put the spikes on any date you want.
rbf_dates = [pd.to_datetime(str(i + 1) + '/1/2020') for i in range(num_rbfs)] 

# And now let's look at the results.
print(rbf_dates)

[Timestamp('2020-01-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-02-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-03-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-04-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-05-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-06-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-07-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-08-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-09-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-10-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-11-01 00:00:00'), Timestamp('2020-12-01 00:00:00')]
In [17]:
# We need a gamma value...
our_gamma = 1/(2*750)

# And now time to make the basis functions!
for i in range(num_rbfs):
    train_df1['rbf_' + str(i)] = train_df1.apply(rbf_date, datestart = rbf_dates[i], gamma = our_gamma, axis = 1)
    test_df1['rbf_' + str(i)] = test_df1.apply(rbf_date, datestart = rbf_dates[i], gamma = our_gamma, axis = 1)
In [19]:
# What does this look like for a year?

In [20]:
# What does this look like for all the data?
train_df1[['rbf_' + str(i) for i in range(num_rbfs)]].plot(figsize = (20,10));

Now we'll use patsy again! In this case, we have a number of other features we'd like to include to the regressor. Rather than selecting the columns with .loc/.iloc or having to manually create the formula, we can instead append the names to a string.

Remember as well that these formulas can become quite complex (i.e. if we included an interaction term, etc...) so it still beneficial to remain in the Patsy paradigm.

In [21]:
# Naming the formula for the linear regression
formula2 = "Temp ~ 0 + Time"
for i in range(num_rbfs):
    formula2 += ' + rbf_' + str(i)

print(formula2)

In [22]:
# Use Patsy to make the required matrices/arrays
y_train1, X_train1 = dmatrices(formula2, data = train_df1)
y_test1, X_test1 = dmatrices(formula2, data = test_df1)

Looking simply at the metrics, we can see that this model is looking much better. In particular, we can see that $P(F^{\star}) = 0$ and we have lower AIC/BIC metrics. Additionally, the p-values of our coefficients are generally close to zero. Given the nature of what the RBF's are doing we can assume that this is capturing at least some of the obvious seasonality. But now let's check out the plots to see how these various curves have been combined:

WOW! That looks much better, since we clearly have smooth plots that generally mimic the data nicely! And unlike encoding each month as a dummy, we don't have steps and jumps that are certainly unrealistic.

Summary¶

So in this notebook, we've done quite a few cool things!

  1. We had an introduction to patsy which can take complicated text formulas and convert these into useful matrices for modeling.
  2. We fit the model with sklearn and extracted the model coefficients. We then fit the model using statsmodels and showed the outputs matched as well as the very rich statistical output available with statsmodels. We then discussed some of the useful metrics for diagnostics.
  3. We created a custom function to create a Gaussian Radial Basis function and applied these to the data and analyzed performance.

Next Steps¶

We obviously didn't do much for this problem and there are several other areas we could have addressed:

Linear Model Problem¶

In this case, there are several other things that could be done.

  1. The data is clearly seasonal and reasonably well-behaved so a Fourier basis function would likely fit the data well and reduce the number of features (the simpler the model, the better).
  2. We can see that temperatures get extreme during the peak of summer (January) and dead of winter (July) but only for about 2 weeks at a time. We may want to incorporate other basis functions for just those time points
  3. There is the chance that there is an interaction between the time feature and the RBFs. While this would be an absolute pain to accomplish normally, with patsy, this is quite simple to include: 
     formula3 = 'Temp ~ 0 + Time*(rbf_0 + rbf_1 + rbf_2 + rbf_3 + rbf_4 + rbf_5 + rbf_6 + rbf_7 + rbf_8 + rbf_9 + rbf_10 + rbf_11)'
  4. We may want to use a Weighted Least Squares model if we felt that the predictions are not reflective of recent history

What Else???¶

Ultimately, we have evidence of some kind of autocorrelation and so our principle assumption (iid observations) is not valid in all likelihood. A better model would try and address the time series components yet allow for some sort of exogenous features. This is really an area where statsmodels offers something that sklearn doesn't do very well. Most of what I have seen in sklearn involves effectively manually adding in autoregressive lags to the data or manually differencing the series. Yet statsmodels has a vast array of time series models, ranging from simple AR models to a number of advanced State Space models. If you have any kind of time series problem, you should be going to statsmodels first.

If you have any interests in seeing statsmodels applied to a Time Series domain problem, please let me know.
